# Changelog Conventions

## Release date placeholder

New changelogs are never created with a concrete date. Use the `RELEASE_DATE` placeholder instead — a GitHub Action replaces it with the actual merge date when the PR lands on `main`.

Apply `RELEASE_DATE` in three places:

1. **Filename** — `changelog/YYYY/RELEASE_DATE-topic.md` (use current year for the folder)
2. **Title inside the file** — `# RELEASE_DATE: My feature title`
3. **SUMMARY.md link** — `* [RELEASE_DATE: My feature title](YYYY/RELEASE_DATE-topic.md)`

❌ `changelog/2026/2026-05-13-cart.md` / `# 2026-05-13: Cart Service - …`
✅ `changelog/2026/RELEASE_DATE-cart.md` / `# RELEASE_DATE: Cart Service - …`

## Changelog header icon

Every changelog file has an `icon` field in its YAML frontmatter. Choose the icon based on the type of change:

| Change type | Icon |
|---|---|
| New feature | `sparkles` |
| Improvement | `wand-sparkles` |
| Major change | `sliders-up` |
| Minor change | `sliders` |
| Deprecation | `hourglass-half` |

Example frontmatter for a new feature:

```yaml
---
icon: sparkles
layout:
  title:
    visible: true
  description:
    visible: true
  tableOfContents:
    visible: true
  outline:
    visible: false
  pagination:
    visible: true
---
```
